segments.text: And would you say that they carried over any customs that changed this community, or were they more or less Americanized by the time that you came in?
I think they've been Americanized to a certain extent, but there have been some Italian farmers in the Brazos Bottom that were, I heard at one time that they worked so hard
that they were able to buy up land.
They made good in the farming part, and they were able to buy up a lot of land that some of the Native Americans weren't ambitious enough to work to get.
I don't know about the other ethnic groups.
You may mention that the blacks, were they more or less in a certain part of the city or the area, the region around here?
Yes.
They were about...
They still live in the sections that they were in.
There are a few that have moved out.
Would you say that they are still as...
They're very good citizens, I think.
I know one black woman who is a very ambitious person for her family.
She has a daughter who's married to a colonel in the army, and this daughter has a nursing degree.
She has two sons who are principals of schools in various places.
And to this day, when her name is mentioned here, everybody knows about her and knows what a really ambitious woman she is.
And she's very highly respected.
Would you say that there have...
there has been a separation, of course, between the whites and the blacks in most things.
Would you say that that is still prevalent or are they coming together closer or were they ever separated?
I don't know that there's been too much change in their lifestyles.
Some of them have much better jobs than we used to have.
But I really don't have contact with them now.
I just don't know.
I don't have any help at all.
And I have no contact with the black people anymore.
You mentioned, I noticed when you were talking about the feeds and how the prices went down when the first supermarket was built here.
Did it seem to be certain owners of stores before that time that kept the prices up?
Yes.
They were old time people in Bryan and they were
It was hard on them to cut prices when the supermarkets came in and brought in lower prices.
Well, how long have you lived in this area, the number of years since, what was the year that you first moved here?
I came to Brown in 1927.
And you say that you had two sons, and they both got their college degrees.
Well, the older boy got his bachelor's degree from the University of Texas.
And then he went on to medical school in Dallas.
The other son went to Galveston for his medical training.
And both took their specialty.
at the same school.
So your two sons, they both left the area at first to gain employment?
Or has the youngest one just finished school?
Oh, no.
He's practiced in Houston for three years.
He was in the Army for two years after his residence in psychiatry.
And then he practiced medicine in Houston for three years.
has just decided to move to this community because he thinks it's a good community.
That's what I was wondering, whether, you know, all your kids, both of your sons had left, or whether, you know, they were here, and so now your youngest son has come back.
He's just been back two weeks, but he's very happy with me.
He plans to stay here, though.
Yes, he plans to stay here.
In fact, he's going to live in this house.
He wants to come home.
I'm selling in the house, and they're going to add to it and rebuild it, and I'm going to an apartment.
And you're staying here then?
In College Station, of course, this is home.
I wouldn't consider anything else.
Well, thank you for the time and the interview.
Well, you're quite welcome.
I hope I've been at least a little helpful to you.
It's been real good.
Thank you again.
You're welcome.
This interview has been with Mrs. William Potts, first name Aris.
She lives at 306 Lee Street in College Station, Texas, and has lived there for quite a number of years.
She came to this community in 1927 to teach high school at Bryan High School, and it was here that she met her husband.
She stated that certain conveniences were already here when she arrived, but there was also quite a few lacking.

I found, by reading old issues of the Bryan Eagle, that, in fact, the first sewer treatment plant was installed in 1913, run by the city of Bryan, and so it had been in operation for several years before she arrived.
She stated that when she came here, sewer service was installed.
She also mentioned that the roads were just gravel.
It was not until November 28, 1929, that the people voted to issue bonds for the purpose of building a system of highways.
Before this, even Highway 6 was not in very good condition and was prone to frequent flooding, such as on November 11, 1929.

Also in the year 1929, stores such as Montgomery Ward announced openings in Bryan, which indicate that the Bryan College Station area had a bright outlook as far as growth, especially when you take into account that this was during Depression years.
The schools were in poor condition except for the one in Bryan where Mrs. Potts taught.
She seemed to be highly pleased with the school.
H. L. Durham was the superintendent of the Bryan system at that time.
Even as late as 1930, Bryan High School was the only school in the area that had a good scholastic program.
She mentioned that her uncle had come to Bryan to open up Allen Academy.
This took place in 1899, and so he was quite established by the time she arrived.

This tends to make me believe, along with a few other remarks such as, I don't have any help at all, inferring that she used to have domestic help, that she and her husband were above average as far as their social and economic levels.
Finally, in 1939, the city of College Station started taking on other responsibilities besides just the college, such as power lines, sewage, and water lines.
They incorporated and began to grow as a city.
Mrs. Potts has seen vast changes take place during her years.
She has gone through such presidents as Hoover, FDR, and Truman.
She has seen a small cluster of professors and other college-connected people form the city of College Station.
She lived for a time in an era where there was no television and people made their own entertainment, of which she played no small part.
She has seen people grow apart with the invention of the television and there seemed to be a twinge of sadness in her voice as she told me how social life had changed.
She has seen College Station and Bryan grow into one big city and Texas A&M grow into a major institution.
She has much knowledge and this interview just barely touches her resources.
